# Self-Healing Test Automation Framework (Knitwell / AFTA)

## Summary

This PR introduces a complete three-tier self-healing locator engine for the
Playwright/TypeScript automation suite, plus a flow-resolution dashboard. When
a locator breaks, the framework resolves it automatically ‚Äî falling back from
the stored primary locator, to generated smart locators, to AI-generated
locators ‚Äî instead of failing the test. Every resolution is recorded and
rendered in a dashboard so healing behaviour is auditable.

Validated end-to-end against the Ann Taylor (EShopWorld) storefront funnel:
homepage ‚Üí search ‚Üí product ‚Üí bag.

---

## Motivation

Retail storefronts (Ann Taylor, Talbots, Chico's) change markup frequently ‚Äî
ids flip between renders, classes are framework-generated, the same logical
control renders twice (mobile + desktop twins). Hard-coded locators rot fast.
This framework keeps tests green across those changes without manual locator
maintenance, and makes every auto-repair visible for review.

---

## What's included

### 1. Three-tier resolution engine (`fallbackEngine.ts`)

Per element, in order:

1. **DB primary** ‚Äî the stored primary locator.
2. **Smart locators** ‚Äî role ‚Üí testId ‚Üí label ‚Üí placeholder ‚Üí text ‚Üí alt ‚Üí
   title ‚Üí css ‚Üí xpath, tried in priority order.
3. **AI healing** ‚Äî GPT-4.1 (Azure OpenAI) generates a locator from live DOM +
   screenshots.

Supporting logic added here:

- **Locator-string parser** (`buildLocator` / `buildBaseLocator`) that
  reconstructs Playwright locators from stored strings, including:
  - `getByRole` with **regex-name** form (`{ name: /‚Ä¶/i }`), which the original
    parser couldn't handle and which crashed the CSS path.
  - Playwright selector suffixes: `>> nth=N`, `>> visible=true`, and `:visible`.
- **Twin-aware validation** (`isValidLocator`): a locator matching several
  elements is still valid if exactly one is visible (mobile/desktop twin), and
  a "soft match" (several visible sharing one accessible name, e.g. product-card
  image + title + quick-view) is accepted with `.first()` and logged loudly for
  audit.
- **`resolveToSingle`** narrows twins/soft-matches to the visible/first match.

### 2. Smart-locator generation (`selfHealing.ts`)

- Extracts element metadata + ancestor/sibling chains.
- Generates the full smart-locator bundle, each candidate uniqueness-checked
  with the twin-aware verdict (`unique` / `visible-one` / `no`).
- **Dynamic-value rejection**: UUIDs, long hashes, framework-generated ids
  (`react`/`mui`/`mat`/`cdk`/`ng` + digits), indexed/positional XPath are all
  refused so generated locators stay stable.
- Notably drops bare `id` as a preferred CSS strategy (Ann Taylor's search
  input id flips between renders); id survives only as a gated last-resort
  XPath candidate.
- Captures element + full-page screenshots (JPEG q70) and a minimized DOM for
  the AI tier.

### 3. AI healing tier (`aiHealing.ts`)

- Multimodal Azure OpenAI call: DOM-as-text prompt + **real image blocks**
  (old element, old page, current page), not pasted base64.
- `imageBlock` returns `null` for missing screenshots so empty/"Not available"
  blocks are never sent; reference images use `low` detail, the current page
  uses `high` (token-cost control).
- Strict-JSON contract with markdown-fence stripping before parse.
- Confidence threshold (‚â•0.7) and dynamic-locator rejection on the AI result.

### 4. Orchestration + resilience (`stepRunner.ts`)

- `step()` routes each element through capture ‚Üí DB/smart ‚Üí AI heal.
- **`CAPTURE_MODE`** learning run: captures every element against a fresh DB
  without resolving or healing.
- **`capturedThisRun`** in-run guard: an element captured mid-run is never
  re-resolved later in the same run (fixes the `search_input` bug where a
  mid-run DB write flipped a "new" element to "existing" and sent it down the
  resolve path against a navigated page).
- **Overlay / welcome-popup handling** for the EShopWorld geo modal:
  graceful dismissal ‚Üí Escape ‚Üí hard DOM removal, plus a per-click guard that
  re-clears the overlay if it re-fires after navigation.
- **Typed errors** that prevent wasted healing cycles:
  - `OverlayInterceptError` ‚Äî locator was correct, a popup blocked the click;
    don't trigger AI healing.
  - `CaptureFailedError` ‚Äî a brand-new element couldn't be captured; there's
    nothing to heal, so surface the real cause instead of the misleading
    "No locator data found".
- `ensureSearchPanelOpen` makes the search-box precondition explicit and
  idempotent.

### 5. Persistence (`db.ts`, `elementRepo.ts`, `healingRepo.ts`)

- Postgres-backed element store; `saveElement` upserts on `element_name` with
  `COALESCE(NULLIF(...))` so blank incoming values never wipe existing
  screenshots/HTML.
- Append-only `healing_logs` audit of every healing attempt (strategy, status,
  attempted locators, error).

### 6. Reporting + dashboard (`flowTracker.ts`, `sink.ts`, `SelfHealingReporter.ts`, `renderHtml.ts`)

- Per-element flow tracking across the run, sharded per worker.
- Reporter merges shards, de-dupes by `elementName`, renders a themed
  dashboard: resilience ring, tier-distribution bar, per-element expandable
  tier traces (dark/light).
- **This PR also unifies the two reporting backends** ‚Äî the reporter now reads
  both `flows/` (capture/DB/smart) and `shards/` (AI tier) and normalizes the
  two flow shapes, so AI-tier flows are no longer dropped from the dashboard.

---

## Validation

- Ann Taylor self-healing funnel spec passes end-to-end (homepage ‚Üí search ‚Üí
  product ‚Üí PDP), exercising capture, DB/smart resolution, overlay handling,
  and the search-panel precondition.
